#####################################################################
# SFS Lab
#
# Student handout directory
#####################################################################

This directory contains the files needed to work through the SFS lab. It is
arranged as a handout-style working directory: start here, edit `sfs-disk.c`,
and use the provided tools to test your work.

Start here. For the normal student workflow, you only need this file,
`SFS_Lab_Writeup.md`, `sfs-api.h`, and the file you edit:

    sfs-disk.c

Repository-level `docs/` files, JSON schema notes, trace internals, and
maintainer notes are optional background. You do not need them to complete the
lab.

Provided support files:

    sfs-api.h       API specification for sfs-disk.c.
    sfs-disk.h      On-disk data structures and constants.
    sfs-support.c   Low-level disk image and mmap support.
    sfs-fsck.c      Filesystem consistency checker.

Suggested order:

    1. Run `make check` once to confirm the handout and tools are working.
    2. Read `SFS_Lab_Writeup.md`.
    3. Read the `sfs_getpos`, `sfs_seek`, and `sfs_rename` comments in
       `sfs-api.h`.
    4. Edit only `sfs-disk.c`.
    5. Run `make test` after each change.
    6. Work through Category A, then B, then C.
    7. Tune performance only after correctness reaches 12/12.

Main test command:

    make test         Run the local autograder.

Setup and cleanup commands:

    make check        Run once before starting, or when the handout looks broken.
    make clean        Remove generated files.

Optional score details:

    make json         Print the local 22-point score as JSON.

The unmodified starter is expected to fail the full autograder because some
functions are intentionally left for you to implement. `make check` passing
means the package is healthy; `make test` is the command for your progress.

SCORING.md explains how to read the local score if you want more detail. The
local score is a self-study signal, not an Autolab prediction.
